<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" standalone="yes"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title>MacOS on Tech Notebook</title><link>https://wiki.deimos.fr/categories/macos/</link><description>Recent content in MacOS on Tech Notebook</description><generator>Hugo</generator><language>en-us</language><lastBuildDate>Thu, 01 May 2025 20:33:41 +0200</lastBuildDate><atom:link href="https://wiki.deimos.fr/categories/macos/index.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><item><title>Mount Disk Images from Command Line</title><link>https://wiki.deimos.fr/Monter_des_images_disque_en_ligne_de_commande/</link><pubDate>Sun, 13 Dec 2009 15:56:00 +0200</pubDate><guid>https://wiki.deimos.fr/Monter_des_images_disque_en_ligne_de_commande/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="introduction">Introduction &lt;a href="#introduction" class="anchor" aria-hidden="true">&lt;i class="material-icons align-middle">link&lt;/i>&lt;/a>&lt;/h2>&lt;p>You may sometimes need to manually mount disk images. Here&amp;rsquo;s how to do it.&lt;/p>
&lt;h2 id="usage">Usage &lt;a href="#usage" class="anchor" aria-hidden="true">&lt;i class="material-icons align-middle">link&lt;/i>&lt;/a>&lt;/h2>


 
 
 

 
 
 
 

 

 &lt;div class="prism-codeblock ">
 &lt;pre id="474b46f" class="language-bash ">
 &lt;code>hdiutil attach somefile.dmg&lt;/code>
 &lt;/pre>
 &lt;/div></description></item><item><title>Viewing Hidden Files and Folders in Mac OS X</title><link>https://wiki.deimos.fr/Voir_les_fichiers_et_dossiers_cach%C3%A9s_sous_Mac_OS_X/</link><pubDate>Sat, 28 Nov 2009 15:59:00 +0200</pubDate><guid>https://wiki.deimos.fr/Voir_les_fichiers_et_dossiers_cach%C3%A9s_sous_Mac_OS_X/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="introduction">Introduction &lt;a href="#introduction" class="anchor" aria-hidden="true">&lt;i class="material-icons align-middle">link&lt;/i>&lt;/a>&lt;/h2>&lt;p>By default Mac OS X doesn&amp;rsquo;t show any hidden files or folders. If you want to see everything, follow these steps.&lt;/p>
&lt;h2 id="usage">Usage &lt;a href="#usage" class="anchor" aria-hidden="true">&lt;i class="material-icons align-middle">link&lt;/i>&lt;/a>&lt;/h2>&lt;p>Show all hidden objects:&lt;/p>



 
 
 

 
 
 
 

 

 &lt;div class="prism-codeblock ">
 &lt;pre id="aebf2f8" class="language-bash ">
 &lt;code>$ defaults write com.apple.Finder AppleShowAllFiles TRUE&lt;/code>
 &lt;/pre>
 &lt;/div>
&lt;p>Swap TRUE with FALSE to turn it off again. Note: Finder must be relaunched afterwards to see the effect. For example like this:&lt;/p>



 
 
 

 
 
 
 

 

 &lt;div class="prism-codeblock ">
 &lt;pre id="525ca26" class="language-bash ">
 &lt;code>$ killall Finder &amp;amp;&amp;amp; open /System/Library/CoreServices/Finder.app&lt;/code>
 &lt;/pre>
 &lt;/div></description></item><item><title>MacFuse + NTFS-3G: Reading and Writing NTFS Partitions on Mac OS X</title><link>https://wiki.deimos.fr/MacFuse_%20_NTFS-3G_:_Lecture_et_%C3%A9criture_de_partitions_NTFS_sur_Mac_OS_X/</link><pubDate>Wed, 31 Oct 2007 06:24:00 +0200</pubDate><guid>https://wiki.deimos.fr/MacFuse_%20_NTFS-3G_:_Lecture_et_%C3%A9criture_de_partitions_NTFS_sur_Mac_OS_X/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="introduction">Introduction &lt;a href="#introduction" class="anchor" aria-hidden="true">&lt;i class="material-icons align-middle">link&lt;/i>&lt;/a>&lt;/h2>&lt;p>Even with the release of Leopard (10.5), everyone thought they would have NTFS write support. We had already missed out on user-friendly native ZFS&amp;hellip;&lt;/p>
